I"<p><a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/neuroplasticity-is-like-protein-folding">Neuroplasticity</a> decreases with age, making children the most <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/biological-reward-systems-are-malleable">malleable</a>,  <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/adolescence-is-exploratory">as epitomized by adolescence</a>. In simulated annealing, a temperature factor informing how exploratory the search is scheduled to progressively decrease, reducing flexibility as the process is narrowing in on strong solutions. In this, decreasing levels of <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/neuroplasticity-enables-cross-modal-compensation">neuroplasticity</a> might be a mechanism underlying a psychological foraging strategy.</p>
